04964nam a22006135i 9780674028845DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20091979mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740288457 a10.4159/97806740288452doi  a(DE-B1597)571760  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBF722 ǂb B76 1996eb 7aPSY0000002bisacsh04a155.41 aBronfenbrenner, Urie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Ecology of Human Development :bExperiments by Nature and Design /cUrie Bronfenbrenner. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2009] 4c©1979  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tContents -- tPart One AN ECOLOGICAL ORIENTATION -- t1. Purpose and Perspective -- t2. Basic Concepts -- tPart Two ELEMENTS OF THE SETTING -- t3. The Nature and Function of Molar Activities -- t4. Interpersonal Structures as Contexts of Human Development -- t5. Roles as Contexts of Human Development -- tPart Three THE ANALYSIS OF SETTINGS -- t6. The Laboratory as an Ecological Context -- t7. Children's Institutions as Contexts of Human Development -- t8. Day Care and Preschool as Contexts of Human Development -- tPart Four BEYOND THE MICROSYSTEM -- t9. The Mesosystem and Human Development -- t10. The Exosystem and Human Development -- t11. The Macrosystem and Human Development -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHere is a book that challenges the very basis of the way psychologists have studied child development. According to Urie Bronfenbrenner, one of the world’s foremost developmental psychologists, laboratory studies of the child’s behavior sacrifice too much in order to gain experimental control and analytic rigor. Laboratory observations, he argues, too often lead to “the science of the strange behavior of children in strange situations with strange adults for the briefest possible periods of time.” To understand the way children actually develop, Bronfenbrenner believes that it will be necessary to observe their behavior in natural settings, while they are interacting with familiar adults over prolonged periods of time. This book offers an important blueprint for constructing such a new and ecologically valid psychology of development. The blueprint includes a complete conceptual framework for analysing the layers of the environment that have a formative influence on the child. This framework is applied to a variety of settings in which children commonly develop, ranging from the pediatric ward to daycare, school, and various family configurations. The result is a rich set of hypotheses about the developmental consequences of various types of environments. Where current research bears on these hypotheses, Bronfenbrenner marshals the data to show how an ecological theory can be tested. Where no relevant data exist, he suggests new and interesting ecological experiments that might be undertaken to resolve current unknowns. Bronfenbrenner’s groundbreaking program for reform in developmental psychology is certain to be controversial. His argument flies in the face of standard psychological procedures and challenges psychology to become more relevant to the ways in which children actually develop. It is a challenge psychology can ill-afford to ignore.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild psychologyxResearch. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh1 aCole, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067422456840uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674028845?locatt=mode:legacy40